As many others have said, most of the quiz parts just straight up don‚Äôt work and when they do they are super unintuitive and confusing to answer. All this said, to me it‚Äôs not a big deal because like I said, the actual Codecademy pro course is amazing and if you are serious about learning programming you aren‚Äôt going to do it on a smartphone. I downloaded this mostly out of curiosity but never had any intention of making it my main method of study. Anyone that‚Äôs dissatisfied with this app and is serious about learning I would strongly encourage you to try Codecademy‚Äôs free version on their website and see if the style fits you and if it does I would say take the plunge as it has been well worth it for me and I am getting insane value for what I paid.

review:
I quote you guys ‚ÄúI mean pacifically those looking to learn any skills pertaining to the field software engineering and/or development a.k.a. ‚Äúholding ‚Äúwhich is a generalised vague summation of software development‚Ä¶I never understood the whole ‚Äúlearn to code‚Äù nonsense‚Äî because, ‚Äúcoding‚Äù in its broadest sense is nothing more than the execution of software‚Ä¶by that definition; anyone capable of running the following function in an IDE is a ‚Äúcoder‚Äù‚Ä¶

print(‚ÄòHello world‚Äô)

Grats!

When I first began learning software development, resources were limited to books and websites with personal blogs‚Ä¶before smart phones, using Windows ‚Äò99.

 I recently began ‚Äòlearning to code‚Äô (I get some more accurate explanation would be remembering to code whilst learning about what‚Äôs changed in almost 15Y‚Äî i‚Äôll admit it was a bit intimidating at first until I realise that just like always (at least when it comes to engineering/tech )Evolution is based in its simplest user friendly experience and so the UX/UI would be easy after a decade and a half of pivoting to finance for the 2nd half of my 20s. My goodness was I right.

I don‚Äôt know how to say this but python is a joke. In either case, I‚Äôve returned to home my craft and I am blessed with a bittersweet life.

I grew up with crippling OCD/autism/ADHD and so the syntax and indentation that really bugs most developers was something I actually enjoy it and C++/CSS.

I am/was uniquely poised for this whole fintech/crypto revolution‚ÄîNeedless to say there were NOT many people that have an educational tantamount to an MBA in finance and Master‚Äôs computer science which is exactly what you need to fully understand fintech. I feel really stupid for paying 300 something bucks for annual subscription at DataCamp when FCC is more than enough in terms of educational resources in Data science/data analysis/machine learning/etc. 

From a former MIT grad: shout-out to the devs at FCC for expediting access to your personal resources, fundamentals and exercises. At this rate I should be up to speed by the end of the quarter! Thanks to ya‚Äôll!

Respectfully,

review:
This is a decent app to supplement the real learning and practice done on the codecademy website, but it is extremely bare-bones, limited, and full of typos and errors on the practice/quiz portions. Sometimes the sample code just says BLANK BLANK BLANK and I have to choose the answers based on the question without having any sample code block to look at and fill in the needed sections.
Sometimes the text colors are completely random in the blocks of code.
Sometimes there are like 4 empty boxes to fill but the answer only requires 2, so you click an answer and it fills in 3 boxes and the next answer fills in the last. 
Some of the problems are phrased strangely e.g. ‚Äúeliminate the answers that aren‚Äôt true‚Äù which sounds like you should click the wrong answers one-by-one until only the right one remains.

 Some of the questions say ‚Äúcreated by‚Äù with a random username as if random people are creating these questions instead of professional programmers, which explains a lot of the mistakes I suppose. The web-based learning is great so far, but the app is only a slightly useful supplement to help retain what you learned with refresher blurbs and buggy quizzes.

review:
I‚Äôve used several different coding applications and the setup of this one is the most strange to me. Why does the content in the lessons keep changing when you leave and come back? Why does the resume button at the top of the page not actually resume your progress in the course but take you to a testing ground? Why don‚Äôt they begin the programming languages at the beginning with the fundamentals? I kept feeling like i was missing out on content because i knew the lesson material changes and i was introduced to several new concepts (which is actually great because I‚Äôm still learning) but wasn‚Äôt taught to the point where i would be able to duplicate the results of the teacher, give a comprehensive understanding of what i was being shown, or felt like i could actually explain what i had learned. Why not have all the material you want to include in the lessons already there so you don‚Äôt have people swipe through five slides and then come back realizing there‚Äôs entirely new content? If i learn a new language i want to learn it well. 
I‚Äôm not an advanced programmer yet so there‚Äôs a lot of things i still don‚Äôt know, and the lessons introduced a page of code, and proceeded to explain one element. I need to know all the details in the beginning, like what this term means, and what this does, and five slides later I didn‚Äôt feel like i was ready to be tested on anything because i missed so much of what was going on.

replyContent: Hi Devlin, we're working on adding GitHub sign in. However you can log in using your username or email and password. If you don't have that information we have instructions to recover it on our Help Center: https://help.codecademy.com/hc/en-us/articles/360007591674-Can-I-login-using-single-sign-on- Let us know if you have any other questions!
